            <ArticleTitle>Octave-wide phase-matched four-wave mixing in dispersion-engineered crystalline microresonators.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>3146-3149</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1364/OL.44.003146</ELocationID>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>In this Letter, we report phase-matched four-wave mixing separated by over one octave in a dispersion-engineered crystalline microresonator. Experimental and numerical results presented here confirm that primary sidebands were generated with a frequency shift up to 140 THz, and that secondary sidebands formed a localized comb structure, known as a clustered comb in the vicinity of the primary sidebands. A theoretical analysis of the phase-matching condition validated our experimental observations, and our results agree well with numerical simulations. These results offer the potential to realize a frequency-tunable comb cluster generator operating from 1 Î¼m to mid-infrared wavelengths with a single and compact device.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
